{{/*
  systemd drop-in hardening for redis-server (Go text/template strict, ADR-010). Context:
  .vars.data_dir/run_dir/log_dir/conf_dir - actual redis write directories under
  ReadWritePaths.

  conf_dir in the RW paths is REQUIRED (day-2): the update_config scenario does CONFIG
  REWRITE (community.redis.config with rewrite:true) - redis-server rewrites redis.conf to
  persist applied directives. Without conf_dir, ProtectSystem=strict keeps /etc read-only,
  so CONFIG REWRITE fails ("Read-only file system") on the first directive that actually
  changed. On create, redis-server does not rewrite the config (starts from a ready-made
  file), but the drop-in is one for the whole lifecycle - conf_dir is needed for day-2.

  WHY a drop-in and not our own unit. Redis is installed by the distro package together
  with its systemd unit redis-server.service. The distro unit cannot be replaced wholesale -
  it carries ExecStart/Type=notify/RuntimeDirectory and is updated together with the package.
  So hardening arrives as an override: /etc/systemd/system/redis-server.service.d/hardening.conf
  on top of the distro unit ([Service] directives are merged, ours take priority).

  SERVICE ACCOUNT. We deliberately do NOT set User/Group in the drop-in. redis is a
  stateful service (prod convention §2/§3): the owned data-dir /var/lib/redis (RDB/AOF)
  requires a stable file-owner uid across restarts/upgrades. The distro package already
  creates the system account redis:redis (stable uid) and the distro unit already runs
  under it. DynamicUser is unsuitable here: files under one run's transient uid would
  belong to a "foreign" uid on the next run. The account comes from the package, manual
  core.user/core.group are not needed.

  HARDENING (prod convention §3, "security first", requirements.md). Stateful variant:
  ProtectSystem=strict + ReadWritePaths under the actual redis write directories
  (data-dir/log/pidfile/socket + conf-dir for day-2 CONFIG REWRITE, see above). WITHOUT
  ReadWritePaths, strict makes all of / read-only and redis would be unable to write
  RDB/AOF/socket/pid/log/redis.conf - a prod incident.

  We deliberately do NOT set MemoryDenyWriteExecute (unlike the Go binaries of exporters).
  redis is written in C, uses jemalloc, and supports loadable modules; MDWE forbids W+X
  mappings and can break the allocator/JIT pages of modules. For stateful redis it is
  safer not to enable MDWE.

  RestrictAddressFamilies carries AF_UNIX: redis listens on BOTH TCP (:6379, redis.conf.tmpl)
  AND can listen on a unix socket. CapabilityBoundingSet= is empty: :6379 (>1024) and the
  socket require no privileges, CAP_NET_BIND_SERVICE is not needed.
*/}}
[Service]
NoNewPrivileges=yes
ProtectSystem=strict
ReadWritePaths={{ .vars.data_dir }} {{ .vars.run_dir }} {{ .vars.log_dir }} {{ .vars.conf_dir }}
ProtectHome=yes
PrivateTmp=yes
ProtectKernelTunables=yes
ProtectControlGroups=yes
RestrictAddressFamilies=AF_INET AF_INET6 AF_UNIX
LockPersonality=yes
RestrictNamespaces=yes
CapabilityBoundingSet=
